\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10.1}{\ignorespaces Gregor Mendel, the Moravian Augustinian monk who is credited for having founded the modern science of genetics\rmarkdownfootnote {\url {https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gregor_Mendel.png}}\relax }}{150}{figure.caption.52}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10.2}{\ignorespaces Characteristics of pea plants Gregor Mendel used in his inheritance experiments\rmarkdownfootnote {\url {https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gregor_Mendel_-_characteristics_of_pea_plants_-_english.png}}\relax }}{151}{figure.caption.53}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10.3}{\ignorespaces P-Generation and F1-Generation: The dominant allele for purple-red flower hides the phenotypic effect of the recessive allele for white flowers. F2-Generation: The recessive trait from the P-Generation phenotypically reappears in the individuals that are homozygous with the recessiv genetic trait.\rmarkdownfootnote {\url {https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Dominant-recessive_inheritance_-_flowers_of_pea_plants.png}}\relax }}{152}{figure.caption.54}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10.4}{\ignorespaces In the F1 generation all individuals have the same genotype and same phenotype expressing the dominant trait (red). In the F2 generation, the phenotypes show a 3:1 ratio. In the genotype 25\% are homozygous with the dominant trait, 50\% are heterozygous genetic carriers of the recessive trait, 25\% are homozygous with the recessive genetic trait and expressing the recessive character.\rmarkdownfootnote {\url {https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Dominant-recessive_inheritance_P_-_F1_-_F2.png}}\relax }}{153}{figure.caption.55}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10.5}{\ignorespaces In \emph {Mirabilis jalapa} and \emph {Antirrhinum majus} are examples for intermediate inheritance. As seen in the F1-generation, heterozygous plants have ``light pink'' flowers---a mix of ``red'' and ``white''. The F2-generation shows a 1:2:1 ratio of red : light pink : white\rmarkdownfootnote {\url {https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Intermediate_inheritance_P_-_F1_-_F2.png}}\relax }}{154}{figure.caption.56}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10.6}{\ignorespaces Segregation and independent assortment are consistent with the chromosome theory of inheritance.\rmarkdownfootnote {\url {https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Independent_assortment_\%26_segregation.svg}}\relax }}{156}{figure.caption.57}%
